english:
  title: Letter to Yi Cheong, Prefect of Yeo-gang County
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I write to Prefect Yi. Long ago there was one Hwan Yeong-jo who in his youth wished to study the martial arts. Someone asked him, "Why do you not study the writings of the sages?" He replied, "To mount a horse and wield the spear, then dismount and discourse on the classics—only thus can one truly say he does not eat the bread of idleness. If a man lacks the skill to preserve himself, how does he differ from beast or fowl?" Yesterday I read your letter, and I saw cause to praise the hearts of your people. Once this region suffered under a hundred li of impoverished custom, trusting in divine providence. Now eighteen fortified villages send forth a militia asking for a commander. Had you not balanced mercy with strength, and tempered authority with benevolence, how could they have harbored righteous hearts? How could they have each fulfilled their nature? Even the fierce-hearted have come to submit. You have set aside the lute upon the hall and taken up the sword from its sheath—this is when the civil transforms and reaches toward the martial.

    Moreover, you of Prefect Yi's house trace your lineage to heaven itself. Your name is as clear as a water's source. Your talents mark you as a hero of this age, and your mind rivals ten thousand men. You are worthy to command brave soldiers and sweep away rebels, clearing not merely the disasters of county and province, but resolving the perils of the realm itself.

    Yet since you already manage military affairs alone, a title befitting your station is surely due. That you have not requested it makes my task difficult. Consider: will you hold both military command and the county magistracy? Or will you change course, seize this opportunity, and establish greater merit? Choose one of these paths and send word promptly so that I may present your case.

    Ban Chao cast down his brush, Kuai En abandoned his fodder—when the dragon in the pool finds water and the heavenly steed catches the wind, what opportunity awaits? The ancient poem says: "Better to be first among a hundred soldiers than to live in shame as a mere scribe." Indeed, great souls despise constraint. Strive to build enduring merit and earn lasting imperial favor. In these pressing times of war, preserve yourself well. And extend words of comfort to all the officers and soldiers in every garrison. Thus I write.
  footnotes:
    - Hwan Yeong-jo (桓榮祖) represents the ideal of the complete man versed in both martial and scholarly pursuits—a classical Confucian ideal particularly valued in medieval East Asia.
    - The eighteen fortified villages (十八砦) represent the local militia forces that have pledged their allegiance and military service.
    - Ban Chao and Kuai En are historical Chinese figures who abandoned their literary pursuits for military glory—Ban Chao famously threw down his brush to pursue a military career, while Kuai En left his humble occupation to serve in the army.
    - The reference to the dragon in the pool finding water and the heavenly steed catching the wind evokes the moment when talent finds its proper sphere and opportunity.
